text: for the last 13 years NASA's Cassini
spacecraft has spied on Saturn and its
many moons turns out this region of
space could hold the greatest secrets of
our solar system here are five of the
most fascinating discoveries Cassini has
given us so far
number one the possibility of alien life
before Cassini Saturn's neighborhood was
relatively average today it's revered as
one of the most likely places to
discover alien life
Cassini first discovered powerful
geysers on Saturn's moon Enceladus the
geysers later revealed a global
subsurface ocean by diving through these
plumes Cassini found heat chemicals that
suggest hydrothermal vents
Lynott seafloor on earth environments
like these are teeming with life so why
not on Enceladus too number two space
lakes before Cassini little was known
about Saturn's moon Titan now we know
it's more earth-like than scientists
could have ever imagined Cassini is
Huygens probe first landed on Titan in
2005 what it saw was the first-ever
lakes beyond earth Titan is the only
place besides Earth with lakes
rainstorms and tides but unlike earth
these are made of liquid methane not
water to date Titan is the furthest moon
where any space probe has landed
number three space storms in 2010 the
biggest storm in our solar system's
history came to life
Cassini's instruments detected signs of
thunder and lightning on Saturn it
measured temperatures in the storm
spiking to 150 degrees Fahrenheit the
updraft would have been powerful enough
to blow away Earth's entire atmosphere
within months Cassini saw the storm wrap
190,000 miles around Saturn that's far
enough to encircle Earth seven and a
half times this went on for nearly a
year before the storm finally died down
number four secrets in Saturn's rings in
Cassini spotted what could be the
formation of a new moon the discovery
suggests
turn one's had an even greater ring
system these ancient rings could have
been where Titan and Enceladus formed
Plus Cassini proves
Saturn's rings aren't uniformly flat
these shadows reveal towering structures
one and a half miles tall it's possible
that unseen moons hidden and Saturn's
rings created them number five
mysterious cloud Saturn's North Pole has
something unique to the entire solar
system
it's called Saturn hexagon the six-sided
shape of these clouds are a topic of
debate Cassini hasn't solved the mystery
but it has revealed that the central
vortex is deeper than expected it sinks
60 miles below Saturn's cloud tops
Cassini conjured another puzzle in 2016
when it's law the hexagon mysteriously
changed colors from blue to gold in 2004
Cassini became the first spacecraft to
ever orbit Saturn this September it's 13
year mission with Saturn will end but
not before it's discoveries made way for
future missions missions that could
solve the grandest mysteries of all
